        Back to Blog
      </a>
      <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl text-cream font-bold leading-tight">
        When to Restore vs. Replace Antique Furniture: A Wylie Craftsman's Honest Take
      </h1>
      <div class="mt-6 flex items-center gap-4 text-cream/60 text-sm">
        <time datetime={publishDate}>February 18, 2025</time>
        <span>&bull;</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Sample Disclaimer -->
  <div class="bg-burgundy text-cream text-center py-4 px-4 border-b-2 border-gold">
    <p class="font-bold text-lg uppercase tracking-wider">For Sample Purposes Only</p>
    <p class="text-cream/80 text-sm mt-1">This blog post is a demo showing what content marketing could look like for your business. It has not been published or attributed to anyone.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Article Content -->
  <article class="py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-charcoal-light leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <p class="text-xl text-charcoal leading-relaxed">
          I get asked this question at least twice a week. Someone calls the shop, describes a piece
          of furniture they found at an estate sale in McKinney or inherited from a grandmother in
          Garland, and wants to know: "Is it worth fixing?" The honest answer is that it depends. But
          after 40-something years of doing this work out of our shop here in Wylie, I have learned
          that most people already know the answer before they pick up the phone.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-wood font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          The Piece Nobody Wanted
        </h2>

        <p>
          A few years back, a woman from Plano brought in a beat-up rocking chair. The finish was
          almost completely gone, one arm was cracked, and the cane seat had a hole big enough to put
          your fist through. She told me her father-in-law had built it by hand in the 1940s. Her
          husband had grown up sitting in that chair while his dad read to him.
        </p>

        <p>
          Now, if you looked at that chair with a price tag in mind, it was not worth much. You could
          go to any furniture store in Dallas and buy a brand new rocker for less than what the
          restoration would cost. But that is not really the question, is it? That chair held
          something no store can sell you. We fixed it. She cried when she picked it up. That is the
          kind of work I got into this business to do.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-wood font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          When Restoration Makes Sense
        </h2>

        <p>
          My family has been working with wood for three generations. My grandfather started in the
          old country, my father carried it on, and I opened ARED in 1980 right here in Wylie,
          Texas. One thing all three of us would agree on is that solid craftsmanship does not go out
          of style. A well-built piece of furniture from 80 or 100 years ago was made with materials
          and techniques you simply do not find in mass-produced furniture today.
        </p>

        <p>Here are the situations where I almost always tell people to go ahead with the restoration:</p>

        <ul class="space-y-3 list-none pl-0">
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gold flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" /></svg>
            <span><strong class="text-charcoal">Solid hardwood construction.</strong> If the frame is oak, walnut, mahogany, or cherry and the joints are real mortise-and-tenon or dovetail, that piece was built to last several lifetimes. A new finish and some joint tightening will make it feel brand new. You cannot buy that quality at a furniture chain in Richardson or Frisco for any price.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gold flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" /></svg>
            <span><strong class="text-charcoal">Sentimental value.</strong> I have restored pieces that traveled across oceans with families. I have repaired dining tables where four generations ate their holiday meals. No dollar amount captures that. If the piece means something to you, the restoration is almost always worth it.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gold flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" /></svg>
            <span><strong class="text-charcoal">It was expensive when it was new.</strong> High-end furniture from brands like Henkel Harris, Baker, Drexel Heritage, or Ethan Allen was made with real craftsmanship. These pieces absolutely deserve a second life. We see a lot of this come through our shop from estates around Allen, McKinney, and the Park Cities.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gold flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" /></svg>
            <span><strong class="text-charcoal">The style is right but the condition is not.</strong> A lot of people in the DFW area are tired of everything looking the same. If you have a unique antique that fits your taste but just looks tired, a refinish or reupholster can transform it for a fraction of what a comparable new piece would cost.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-wood font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          When It Might Be Time to Let Go
        </h2>

        <p>
          I will be straight with you, because I think that is more helpful than telling everyone
          what they want to hear. There are cases where I have told customers that a restoration does
          not make financial sense.
        </p>

        <p>
          Flat-pack furniture and pieces made primarily from particleboard or MDF were not designed
          for longevity. The materials break down in ways that are difficult and expensive to repair
          properly. If the structural material itself is failing, not just the finish or upholstery,
          sometimes it is more practical to start fresh.
        </p>

        <p>
          Water damage is the other one to watch for. A little surface damage from a glass ring? We
          fix that all day long. But if a piece sat in a flooded garage in Rowlett or Mesquite and
          the wood itself is warped, delaminated, or growing mold deep in the grain, there is a
          limit to what restoration can accomplish. I would rather be honest about that upfront than
          take someone's money for a job that will not hold up.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-wood font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          The Most Common Mistake I See in DFW
        </h2>

        <p>
          People wait too long. I cannot tell you how many times someone has brought in a piece and
          said, "I have had this sitting in my garage for five years meaning to get it fixed." Texas
          heat and humidity are brutal on furniture. A garage in Wylie or Sachse can hit 130 degrees
          in the summer. Wood expands, contracts, and cracks. Veneer lifts. Glue joints fail. Fabric
          gets musty and attracts pests.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you have a piece you care about, the best time to get it looked at is now. The second
          best time is before the next Texas summer.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-wood font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          What a Typical Restoration Looks Like
        </h2>

        <p>
          People sometimes picture restoration as just slapping some stain on a table and calling it
          done. The reality is more involved than that, and I think it helps to understand the
          process so you know what you are paying for.
        </p>

        <p>
          For a typical antique table or dresser, we start by assessing the piece at our shop on
          Regency Drive in Wylie. We look at the wood species, the construction method, the type of
          existing finish, and the extent of the damage. From there we give you an honest estimate
          and a timeline.
        </p>

        <p>
          The actual work might include disassembling loose joints, re-gluing with proper adhesive
          for that wood species, repairing or replacing damaged veneer, carefully stripping the old
          finish without damaging the wood underneath, sanding to the right grit, applying stain if
          needed, and building up a new finish coat by coat. For upholstery work, we tear the piece
          down to the bare frame, replace springs, webbing, foam, and fabric, and put it all back
          together so it is comfortable and beautiful.
        </p>

        <p>
          Most projects take two to six weeks. We offer free pickup and delivery anywhere in the DFW
          metroplex, from Fort Worth to Garland, Frisco to Arlington. You do not even have to figure
          out how to fit a dresser in your car.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-wood font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          A Quick Word on DIY
        </h2>

        <p>
          I am not going to tell you never to refinish furniture yourself. If you enjoy it and you
          are working on a piece that is not irreplaceable, go for it. But I will tell you this: we
          get a lot of rescue jobs from well-intentioned DIY attempts. Someone watches a video,
          buys the wrong stripper, sands through the veneer, or uses a finish that does not bond to
          the original. On an antique with real value, those mistakes can be costly or impossible to
          reverse.
        </p>

        <p>
          If the piece matters to you, at least get a professional opinion first. A five-minute phone
          call with us might save you a lot of heartache. We have had people call from Murphy,
          Lucas, and as far as Anna just to ask a quick question, and we are always happy to point
          you in the right direction, even if the answer is "you can handle this one yourself."
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-wood font-bold mt-12 mb-4">
          The Bottom Line
        </h2>

        <p>
          Good furniture was made to last. The people who built it put real skill and real materials
          into every piece, and that kind of work deserves to be preserved. If your great-aunt's
          china cabinet is sitting in a storage unit in Dallas gathering dust, or your grandmother's
          dining set is in the garage in Plano because the finish is shot, give us a call. We will
          tell you honestly whether it makes sense to restore it, and if it does, we will make it
          beautiful again.
        </p>

        <p>
          That is what we have been doing since 1980, and it is what we plan to keep doing for a
          long time.
        </p>

      </div>

